*!TEXT_COMPONENT 30:640:30:640:1214:961:Times New Roman:10:13:0:400:0:0:0:0:1:1:0:4:0
*This example calculates the auxiliary energy necessary to provide a hot water flow at 45 �C with a solar-assisted water heater.  
*
*[1] Weather data from Madison, WI (TMY3) is used.  In the weather data reader, the surface (for the collector) is set to a 45-degree slope, facing due south, with a fixed position (no solar tracking).
*[2] The solar loop pump circulates fluid at 160 kg/hr and consumes power at 240 kJ/hr whenever the pump is 'on'. 
*[3] The total flat plate collector area is 4 m^2. In this case, the solar loop flow rate of 160 kg/hr matches the tested flow rate of 40 kg/hr-m2; while this is not strictly necessary, the efficiency will differ slightly from that calculated from the efficiency equation if the actual flow rate per square meter is greater or less than the tested flow rate. Efficiency is modeled as a function of collector inlet temperature (efficiency mode 1), and the 2nd-order ASHRAE model is used for incidence angle modifiers (Optical mode 2).
*[4] The vertical cylindrical storage tank volume is 0.5 m^3. It is modeled as a stratified (temperature varies with height) tank with six vertical nodes. The solar loop is connected to inlet/outlet pair 1, and the domestic load is connected to inlet/outlet pair 2. Fluid from the collectors enters the tank at a height of (0.67 x 1.8-m = 1.2-m) and exits the tank at the bottom. Domestic water enters the tank at the bottom and exits at the top.  The auxiliary heater and thermostat are placed in the tank at a height of (0.75 x 1.8-m = 1.35-m). The tank ambient environment is constant at 20 �C.
*[5] The differential controller turns the pump 'on' when the temperature difference between the collector and the tank bottom is >= 10 �C and 'off' when the difference is <= 2 �C. It will also turn the pump off if the temperature at the top of the tank reaches or exceeds 100 �C. 
*[6] The tank stat will call for auxiliary heat when the temperature at the thermostat location is at or below 59 �C. It will turn off auxiliary heat when the temperature at the thermostat is at or above 61 �C. 
*[7] qAux Tank applies 9000 [kJ/hr] of energy to the auxiliary location in the tank whenever the tank stat calls for auxiliary heat. 
*[8] The 'Daily Load' calculator multiplies the forcing function output by 200 kg/day daily domestic water use to get the hourly domestic load mass flow rate. The incoming domestic water temperature is constant at 15 �C. 
*[9] The tempering valve controller monitors both the incoming temperature of the domestic load and the load outlet temperature of the tank. It directs a portion of the load flow through the storage tank and a portion to bypass the tank as needed such that the mixed temperature of both streams at the outlet of the tank will equal the tempered setpoint of 45 �C.
*
*To show the plotters, printers, and integrators in this project, go to View -> Show Layers -> and select the 'Outputs' layer. 
* 
*!TEXT_COMPONENT_END
